<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-12-16T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-12-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="593" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d593">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/14827: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-12-16T16:00:00-05:00">December
                                    16, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>303. For the Ambassador from the President. In view of the disruption of
                            mail service, I am acknowledging by telegraph the receipt of your letter
                            of November 19 in which you presented an estimate of the situation in
                            China. I found your letter of interest and of value, and I want you to
                            know that during these critical days when the United States and China
                            are fighting side by side against common enemies you and the gallant
                            Government to which you are accredited are very much in my thoughts.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>